			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1408">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I read Heather King&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/27">The Trial</a>&rdquo; [May 2007] in complete disbelief. Why would anyone who has been treated as badly as she has attempt to forgive the person who mistreated her? Her boss used her in a shameful manner, insulting her dignity, and all she can think about is how to forgive him. To my mind this attitude represents a serious flaw in Christian philosophy. Her boss is clearly someone with no respect for other human beings, and therefore deserves no respect or consideration from anyone else. I fail to understand what Christians are trying to accomplish with such feeble thinking.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Name Withheld<br></p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1682">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>In the <a href="/issues/379/correspondence">July 2007 Correspondence</a> Name Withheld questions the &ldquo;feeble thinking&rdquo; behind Christian forgiveness. To me forgiveness is about letting go of anger and resentment. Like everyone, I have felt these strong emotions, but I&rsquo;ve learned to let them go, because they eat away at me, and I do not want to be devoured. Life is too short and too full of better things. When we indulge our anger and let it dominate our thoughts, we inflict more harm on ourselves than on anyone else.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Mary F. Mullane<br>Benton, Arkansas</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

